✅ Implementing Error Handling with Server-Generated requestId (Used Only in Exception Class)

Since you don’t want to use filters or interceptors and only need requestId inside the exception handler, here’s a clean and production-ready way to handle errors:

📌 Step 1: Define the Error Response DTO

Create a DTO to return structured error responses.

package jp.co.mycompany.servicing.dto;

import lombok.AllArgsConstructor;
import lombok.Data;
import lombok.NoArgsConstructor;

import java.time.LocalDateTime;
import java.util.List;

@Data
@AllArgsConstructor
@NoArgsConstructor
public class ErrorResponseDTO {
    private String code;       // HTTP Status Code (400, 500, etc.)
    private String message;    // General error message
    private List<ErrorDetailDTO> details; // Specific field errors (if applicable)
    private LocalDateTime timestamp; // When the error occurred
    private String requestId;  // Unique request ID (generated in exception handler)
}

Define an additional DTO for field validation errors.

@Data
@AllArgsConstructor
@NoArgsConstructor
public class ErrorDetailDTO {
    private String field; // The field that caused the error
    private String issue; // Description of the issue
}

📌 Step 2: Implement the Global Exception Handler

Use @RestControllerAdvice to catch exceptions globally and generate requestId inside the exception handler.

package jp.co.mycompany.servicing.exception;

import jp.co.mycompany.servicing.dto.ErrorDetailDTO;
import jp.co.mycompany.servicing.dto.ErrorResponseDTO;
import org.springframework.http.HttpStatus;
import org.springframework.http.ResponseEntity;
import org.springframework.validation.FieldError;
import org.springframework.web.bind.MethodArgumentNotValidException;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.ExceptionHandler;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestControllerAdvice;

import java.time.LocalDateTime;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.UUID;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

@RestControllerAdvice
public class GlobalExceptionHandler {

    private static final String ERROR_REQUEST_ID_PREFIX = "ERR-";

    // 🛑 Handle Validation Errors (400 Bad Request)
    @ExceptionHandler(MethodArgumentNotValidException.class)
    public ResponseEntity<ErrorResponseDTO> handleValidationException(MethodArgumentNotValidException ex) {
        List<ErrorDetailDTO> details = ex.getBindingResult().getAllErrors().stream()
                .map(error -> new ErrorDetailDTO(
                        ((FieldError) error).getField(),
                        error.getDefaultMessage()
                ))
                .collect(Collectors.toList());

        ErrorResponseDTO errorResponse = new ErrorResponseDTO(
                "400",
                "Invalid parameter value",
                details,
                LocalDateTime.now(),
                generateRequestId() // Generate requestId here
        );

        return new ResponseEntity<>(errorResponse, HttpStatus.BAD_REQUEST);
    }

    // 🛑 Handle Business Logic Errors (e.g., Invalid Input)
    @ExceptionHandler(IllegalArgumentException.class)
    public ResponseEntity<ErrorResponseDTO> handleIllegalArgument(IllegalArgumentException ex) {
        ErrorResponseDTO errorResponse = new ErrorResponseDTO(
                "400",
                "Invalid input",
                List.of(new ErrorDetailDTO("general", ex.getMessage())),
                LocalDateTime.now(),
                generateRequestId()
        );

        return new ResponseEntity<>(errorResponse, HttpStatus.BAD_REQUEST);
    }

    // 🛑 Handle Generic Exceptions (500 Internal Server Error)
    @ExceptionHandler(Exception.class)
    public ResponseEntity<ErrorResponseDTO> handleGenericException(Exception ex) {
        ErrorResponseDTO errorResponse = new ErrorResponseDTO(
                "500",
                "Internal Server Error",
                List.of(new ErrorDetailDTO("general", ex.getMessage())),
                LocalDateTime.now(),
                generateRequestId()
        );

        return new ResponseEntity<>(errorResponse, HttpStatus.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR);
    }

    // ✅ Generate a unique requestId for debugging purposes
    private String generateRequestId() {
        return ERROR_REQUEST_ID_PREFIX + UUID.randomUUID().toString();
    }
}

📌 Step 3: Use Validation in DTOs

Make sure request DTOs use @Valid for field validation.

package jp.co.mycompany.servicing.dto;

import jakarta.validation.constraints.Size;
import lombok.Data;

@Data
public class FinancialInstitutionSearchConditions {

    @Size(min = 3, max = 10, message = "Financial Institution Code must be between 3 and 10 characters")
    private String financialInstitutionCode;

    @Size(min = 3, max = 10, message = "Branch Code must be between 3 and 10 characters")
    private String financialInstitutionBranchCode;

    private String order;

    @Size(max = 50, message = "Name Kana cannot exceed 50 characters")
    private String nameKana;

    @Size(max = 50, message = "Name cannot exceed 50 characters")
    private String name;
}

📌 Step 4: Ensure Controller Uses @Valid

Ensure your controller uses @Valid to trigger validation.

package jp.co.mycompany.servicing.controller;

import jp.co.mycompany.servicing.dto.FinancialInstitutionDTO;
import jp.co.mycompany.servicing.dto.FinancialInstitutionSearchConditions;
import jp.co.mycompany.servicing.service.FinancialInstitutionService;
import jakarta.validation.Valid;
import lombok.RequiredArgsConstructor;
import org.springframework.http.ResponseEntity;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.*;

import java.util.List;

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/common/financialInstitution")
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class FinancialInstitutionController {

    private final FinancialInstitutionService service;

    @PostMapping("/search")
    public ResponseEntity<List<FinancialInstitutionDTO>> searchInstitutions(
            @Valid @RequestBody FinancialInstitutionSearchConditions searchConditions) {
        List<FinancialInstitutionDTO> results = service.searchInstitutions(searchConditions);
        return ResponseEntity.ok(results);
    }
}

📌 How This Works
	1.	Validation Errors (400 Bad Request)
	•	If financialInstitutionCode is too short, Spring triggers MethodArgumentNotValidException.
	•	The handler catches it and returns a structured JSON with the generated requestId.
Example Response:

{
  "code": "400",
  "message": "Invalid parameter value",
  "details": [
    {
      "field": "financialInstitutionCode",
      "issue": "Financial Institution Code must be between 3 and 10 characters"
    }
  ],
  "timestamp": "2024-02-28T12:30:00",
  "requestId": "ERR-123e4567-e89b-12d3-a456-426614174000"
}


	2.	Business Logic Errors (IllegalArgumentException)
	•	If the service layer throws IllegalArgumentException, it returns 400 Bad Request with the requestId.
	3.	Generic Exceptions (500 Internal Server Error)
	•	If something unexpected happens (like a database error), the system catches it and assigns a unique requestId for tracking.

✅ Final Summary

Requirement	Implemented?
Generate requestId	✅ Inside GlobalExceptionHandler
Use requestId only in error responses	✅ Yes
Include requestId in validation errors	✅ Yes
Include requestId in system failures (500 errors)	✅ Yes
No filters, MDC, or interceptors	✅ Yes

